TRIP COMMENTS: In spite of the a daunting forecast for 50% rain, cool and breezy weather, the 6 INTREPIDS birded this wonderful (and very, very soggy) area.  We actually saw/heard 39 species!  Plus, we got good looks at several species, with some of the birds staying in our binoculars long enough to be able to see and then to talk about the field marks and vocalizations being made.  Leaving 3 Forks, we warmed up and dried off a bit by stopping for a cup of hot jo at a local coffee place, then headed to Snoqualmie Falls to see the juvenile Peregrine Falcons on the scrape.  Whenever the heavy mist would part long enough, we could see at least 3 of the 4 young falcons, who just a month ago were white and fuzzy fluf balls.  Now, as large and as dark gray as their parents, they are likely hours or days from fledging.  What a neat morning from start to finish!  I'm proud of all of us for hanging in there despite such miserable birding conditions.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Wow, what a way to brighten up a soggy, gray meadow!

It was a thrill to pull into Lake Sam's parking lot and see at least 8 BLACK SWIFTS, several VAUX'S SWIFTS and swallows bug catching directly overhead!  Sharon Aagaard and Stan Wood birded with 20 others at Eastside Audubon's monthly bird walk at Lake Sammamish State Park on June 11, 2013, from 8 am to noon. Weather-wise, it was mostly sunny with partial clouds, 10-12 mph winds and temps in the mid to high 50s. HIGHLIGHTS: 2 of the 3 escaped SWAN GEESE are still there; 1 male CINNAMON TEAL was hanging with the Mallards on the sandy bank (thanks Ollie!); 1 OSPREY; 1 COOPER'S HAWK; 4 BALD EAGLES of various ages; at least 4 SPOTTED SANDPIPERS; at least 12 BAND-TAILED PIGEONS; 8 BLACK SWIFT; 4 VAUX'S SWIFT; 1 ANNA'S HUMMINGBIRD; 4 RUFOUS HUMMINGBIRDS; 2 BELTED KINGFISHERS; 4 RED-BREASTED SAPSUCKERS; 8 WESTERN WOOD-PEWEES; 10 WILLOW FLYCATCHERS; 1 PACIFIC-SLOPE FLYCACTHER; 8 WARBLING VIREOS; a 5 SWALLOW morning (no Bank); 20 SWAINSON'S THRUSHES; 8 BLACK-HEADED GROSBEAKS; 1 LAZULI BUNTING (thanks Sara!); 6 BULLOCK'S ORIOLES; and 4 PURPLE FINCHES. 53 species for the day; 105 for the year. The next bird walk is JULY 23. No pre-registration, just show up depending on your mood or the weather. Since this is a state park, a Discover Pass is necessary to park ($10 daily, $30 annual). We meet in the large parking lot to the left just inside the main park entrance (not the boat launch entrance).

TRIP COMMENTS: Sharon Aagaard and Stan Wood birded with 13 other birders at Eastside Audubon's monthly bird walk at Lake Sammamish State Park on May 21, 2014, from 8:10 am to 12:15 pm. We enjoyed cloudy skies, 3-4 mph winds, with temps ranging from 52 to 59 degrees F. HIGHLIGHTS: WOOD DUCK pair; 6 female COMMON MERGANSERS flying rapidly and low through the trees at both beaches, with birds landing & almost disappearing in two possible nesting trees; 2 GREEN HERON adults, one flying above the grassy area at Sunset Beach and the other flying low along Issaquah Creek towards the mouth; heard the "wheat, wheat, wheat" call and saw 4 SPOTTED SANDPIPERS (3 on the sandy "islands" at the mouth of Issaquah Creek and 1 in the cove at Tibbits Beach; 7 BAND-TAILED PIGEONS; 2 RED-BREASTED SAPSUCKERS "mewing" and tending sapwells; 1 WESTERN WOOD-PEWEE making its "pee-eeer" call; 2 PACIFIC-SLOPE FLYCATCHERS hopefully setting up house in the large cottonwood forest just south of the Sunset Beach Parking lot; 1 HUTTON'S VIREO singing in the cottonwood forest; 4 WARBLING VIREOS, with 1-2 making a nest midway up in a tree on the west side of the old apple orchard; 4 SWAINSON'S THRUSHES, singing and calling; 30 CEDAR WAXWINGS all throughtout the park; Warblers:  10 YELLOW, 1 TOWNSEND'S, 6 COMMON YELLOWTHROAT, & 4 WILSON'S; 2 WESTERN TANAGERS; 2 BLACK-HEADED GROSBEAK; 1 male LAZULI BUNTING in the overgrown meadow just to the west of Issaquah Creek; at least 6 BULLOCK'S ORIOLE were flying and chattering throughout the park (we only saw one female); & 6 PURPLE FINCH.  60 species for the day; and 108 species for the year. The next bird walk is Monday, JUNE 23. No pre-registration, just show up depending on your mood or the weather. Since this is a state park, a Discover Pass is necessary to park ($10 daily, $30 annual). We meet in the large parking lot to the left just inside the main park entrance, now signed as the Costco Parking lot but we meet at the far end towards the lake (not the boat launch entrance).

HIGHLIGHTS: WOOD DUCK pair; 6 female COMMON MERGANSERS flying rapidly and low through the trees at both beaches, with birds landing & almost disappearing in two possible nesting trees; 2 GREEN HERON adults, one flying above the grassy area at Sunset Beach and the other flying low along Issaquah Creek towards the mouth; heard the "wheat, wheat, wheat" call and saw 4 SPOTTED SANDPIPERS (3 on the sandy "islands" at the mouth of Issaquah Creek and 1 in the cove at Tibbits Beach; 7 BAND-TAILED PIGEONS; 2 RED-BREASTED SAPSUCKERS "mewing" and tending sapwells; 1 WESTERN WOOD-PEWEE making its "pee-eeer" call; 2 PACIFIC-SLOPE FLYCATCHERS hopefully setting up house in the large cottonwood forest just south of the Sunset Beach Parking lot; 1 HUTTON'S VIREO singing in the cottonwood forest; 4 WARBLING VIREOS, with 1-2 making a nest midway up in a tree on the west side of the old apple orchard; 4 SWAINSON'S THRUSHES, singing and calling; 30 CEDAR WAXWINGS all throughtout the park; Warblers:  10 YELLOW, 1 TOWNSEND'S, 6 COMMON YELLOWTHROAT, & 4 WILSON'S; 2 WESTERN TANAGERS; 2 BLACK-HEADED GROSBEAK; 1 male LAZULI BUNTING in the overgrown meadow just to the west of Issaquah Creek; at least 6 BULLOCK'S ORIOLE were flying and chattering throughout the park (we only saw one female); & 6 PURPLE FINCH.  60 species for the day; and 108 species for the year. The next bird walk is Monday, JUNE 23. No pre-registration, just show up depending on your mood or the weather. Since this is a state park, a Discover Pass is necessary to park ($10 daily, $30 annual). We meet in the large parking lot to the left just inside the main park entrance, now signed as the Costco Parking lot but we meet at the far end towards the lake (not the boat launch entrance).
SPECIES COMMENTS: very quick flyby male in the meadow to the west of Issaquah Creek

Birding LSSP with Carl Haynie.  Cloudy and cool (low 50s-60s), 3-7 mph winds.  HIGHLIGHT:  While scanning for birds at the mouth of Issaquah Creek, Carl called out "Eastern Kingbird"!  I saw where he was looking, and both of us watched as it fluttered over the top of a small row of short willows on the west sandbar.  It perched at the top for about 20+ seconds, then flew off, rising high to the northeast (towards the boat launch) and disappear.
SPECIES COMMENTS: He was singing and perched at the top of blackberry bushes in the overgrown, former meadow.  Directions:  in the SE corner of the Sunset Beach parking lot, walk the wide trail through the large cottonwood forest, go left at the old apple orchard clearing, cross the footbridge in the left corner, continue walking south on the narrow, overgrown trail, keeping the creek on your left, listen and scan the tops of bushes throughout this area

SPECIES COMMENTS: One bird at E edge of S meadow, just downhill from the chapel.  First heard calling, then it popped up for good views.  Then a second bird encountered at W edge of S meadow, near the empid.  Since I walked directly from one spot to the other, and these spots are about 1/3 of a mile apart, the odds seem much better that these were 2 different birds.  Only my second record for the park.  Matt Dufort saw a third bird today also.

A very nice outing with lots of good birds. It seems that I missed the bird of the morning though, as another birder saw 2 BLOY flying over - I was at West Point around 6:50am, and then again around 10:30am, so the second time I might have just missed them. Cloudy, low to mid 50s, light showers about half the time that mostly did not affect bird activity too much, 5 mph S wind shifted to 5 mph N wind. Baby harbor seal at the point, and harbor porpoises and sea lions offshore.----
